review_text: MMFF 2014: (1/8)a nostalgic movie for me.nung bata ako bumili si mama ng CD and this is the movie, that time siguro alam niya na na gay ako and I want to watch this movie talaga, however, 'di ko sinasabi kasi magagalit sa akin yung papa ko, then I think 1st or 2nd week ng january, sabi ni mama may surprise daw siya sakin, then pinakita niya sakin yung CD ng movie na ito, grabe yung tuwa ko talaga that time just because of this movie.anyways, if I will review this movie, for me talagang mas maganda yung unang film, the story is interesting, isa talaga ito sa mg movie na nagsasabing gays are strong and resilientâ€”nag-focus siya sa comedy pero if we look at it, sobrang daming pinagdaanan ni benjamin para patunayan ulit yung sarili niya, mas mabigat lang talaga yung naunang movie for me, and mas nakakatawa rin.the casttt, kaya gusto ko rin itong mapanood before kasi nandito si sir chief HAHAHA.

Nonsensical. Messy. Parodic.Mas interesting yung story nung first movie. Umikot lang talaga yung kwento sa pagconvinced kay Bimbee about bombs. Wala masyadong naglaland na jokes. Ang gulo rin minsan ng transition. May mga eksena na biglang magiiba and walang context sa previous na eksena. Yung ending, bakit ganon. Ginawang video games yung paglalaban. Out of context din na naging just dance yung pagpigil ng pagsabog ng bomba. Wala masyadong character development. Narealized ni Benjie pagkakamali then okay na ulit lahat. Tsaka yung opening, ang random ng plants vs. zombies. Nagstick na lang sana sa paggamit nung mga weapons.
The ultimate definition of a sequel we never needed.

nvm hindi pala sisterakas...eto ata yung may pinakamaraming pa-time capsulein retrospect, praybeyt benjamin is groundbreaking. a gay-led motion picture that was once the highest grossing film in the country. and all because of a nameâ€”vice ganda. from then on, lahat ng films ni vice, nagiging highest grossing. ang celebrity status niya ay nasa upper echelon na. people see vice films because it's vice. came this sequel. two ingredients for its immediate success: first film being an instant cult classic + household name = highest grossing film. but, the lost potential is palpable. i wonder what it would've been like if the sequel focused more on the LGBTQ+ spectrum getting in the military (since it's one of the messages of its predecessor). nonetheless, it has its moments. it's watermarked by the pop culture era that was occuring at the time. and the films serves its purposeâ€”to bring joy and laughter. and sometimes, that's enough.
